PRINTING CODE. Amendments: Whenever an existing statute (or a section of the Indiana
Constitution) is being amended, the text of the existing provision will appear in this style type,
additions will appear in this style type, and deletions will appear in this style type.
Additions: Whenever a new statutory provision is being enacted (or a new constitutional
provision adopted), the text of the new provision will appear in this style type. Also, the
word NEW will appear in that style type in the introductory clause of each SECTION that adds
a new provision to the Indiana Code or the Indiana Constitution.
Conflict reconciliation: Text in a statute in this style type or this style type reconciles conflicts
between statutes enacted by the 2025 Regular Session of the General Assembly.
HOUSE BILL No. 1413
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning
health.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 16-37-6 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE AS
2 A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
3 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 6. Maternal and Infant Health Care Statistic Annual
5 Report
6 Sec. 1. The state department shall collaborate with the following
7 in the preparation of the report required under this chapter:
8 (1) The office of the secretary of family and social services.
9 (2) The department of child services.
10 (3) The professional licensing agency.
11 (4) The statewide maternal mortality review committee
12 established under IC 16-50-1-3.
13 (5) Any other state entity that has data relevant to the
14 information required to be reported under this chapter.
15 Sec. 2. (a) Before April 1 of each year, the state department shall
16 prepare a report compiling statistics for the previous calendar year
17 in comparison to statistics from 2021 before the abortion
2026 IN 1413—LS 6647/DI 104

2
1 restrictions were enacted following the 2022 special session of the
2 general assembly. The report must include the following
3 information concerning 2021 and the previous calendar year:
4 (1) The number of births in Indiana.
5 (2) The number of stillborn births in Indiana.
6 (3) The number of infant deaths in Indiana.
7 (4) The number of maternal deaths in Indiana.
8 (5) The number of child investigation cases performed by the
9 department of child services, and the number of those cases
10 that were substantiated.
11 (6) The number of obstetricians and gynecologists that are
12 practicing in Indiana.
13 (7) The number of Indiana medical residents who intend to
14 specialize in obstetrics or are gynecologists who leave Indiana
15 to practice in another state.
16 (8) Access to maternal and infant health care, including
17 pregnancy related and postpartum care, in Indiana and
18 whether access has decreased in comparison to 2021.
19 (9) Access to primary care services in Indiana and whether
20 access has decreased in comparison to 2021.
21 (10) The cost of maternal and infant health care in Indiana
22 and whether the cost has increased since 2021.
23 (11) The number of deliveries of babies reimbursed under
24 Medicaid and a comparison to the number of deliveries
25 reimbursed under Medicaid in 2021.
26 (12) The amount of Medicaid reimbursement provided to
27 Planned Parenthood in 2021 and whether those recipients
28 have found an alternative provider.
29 (13) The impact of Medicaid costs on maternal and infant
30 health care.
31 (14) Any other cost savings or increases to Indiana.
32 (b) The state department shall do the following:
33 (1) Post the report on the state department's website.
34 (2) Submit the report to the general assembly in an electronic
35 format under IC 5-14-6.
